BOX 1 — Task entry point: What triggers this workflow? What is the desired output?
Trigger: Preparation for the weekly New Frontiers of Sound Education Team meeting.
Desired Output: A professional meeting agenda that summarizes outstanding action items, identifies discussion topics, and organizes the meeting into a logical sequence.
BOX 2 — Data inputs: What information goes in? Data sensitivity classification (Low/Med/High):
Inputs:
•	Previous meeting notes and Zoom AI summaries stored in Box 
•	Action item lists 
•	Project updates 
•	Calendar deadlines 
•	Standing agenda items
Data Sensitivity: Medium
(Internal project documentation only; no FERPA-, HIPAA-, or other protected data.)
BOX 3 — AI tool selected + rationale: Why this tool for this task? Is it institutionally approved?
Tool: ChatGPT connected to institutional Box documentation.
Why: ChatGPT efficiently searches, summarizes, and synthesizes information across multiple meeting notes, reducing the time required to locate previous decisions and unfinished action items. But really, because there is a built in MCP enabled secure access integration between ChatGPT and Box; whereas the Claude integration does not have MCP secure access.
Institutionally Approved: Yes, provided it is used only with institutionally approved Box integration and appropriate institutional data governance requirements.
BOX 4 — Prompt strategy: What prompting approach (zero-shot, few-shot, CoT)? Role specification?
Approach:
•	Role prompting 
•	Few-shot prompting 
•	Iterative refinement (cyborg interaction) 
Example role:
"You are an administrative project coordinator helping prepare a meeting agenda from previous meeting notes."
Typical prompts:
•	Summarize outstanding action items. 
•	Identify recurring discussion topics. 
•	Draft an agenda grouped by Updates, Discussion, Decisions Needed, and Action Items. 
•	Suggest missing follow-up items. 
BOX 5 — AI output review checkpoint: What specifically do you check? For accuracy? Tone? Bias? Completeness?
Before using the agenda I check:
•	Every action item matches the original meeting notes. 
•	Completed items have been removed (AI doesn’t know what happens between meetings that isn’t documented). 
•	Deadlines are accurate. 
•	Meeting priorities reflect current organizational needs. 
•	Tone matches our team's communication style. 
•	No confidential or inappropriate information is included.
BOX 6 — Human verification step (REQUIRED): What human action confirms quality before the output is used?
I compare every AI-generated agenda item against the original Box meeting notes and current project status to verify that:
•	no action items were invented, 
•	no important topics were omitted, 
•	priorities accurately reflect current team needs. 
Only after this verification do I approve the agenda for distribution.
BOX 7 — Output + disclosure decision: Format, destination, and disclosure action (if any):
Output Format:
•	Meeting agenda in Box Notes
•	Email attachment (in Calendar invite) 
•	Shared Box document
Destination:
New Frontiers of Sound Education Team.
Disclosure Decision:
No external disclosure is necessary because AI serves as an internal drafting and organizational tool while I verify all content and remain fully responsible for the final agenda. If institutional policy changes to require disclosure of substantive AI assistance, I would follow that policy.

Collaboration Style
Primary Style: Centaur
This workflow is a centaur model because responsibilities are intentionally divided. AI performs tasks inside the current technological frontier (retrieving information, summarizing notes, and drafting the agenda structure). I perform the frontier-outside tasks of verifying accuracy, setting priorities, incorporating undocumented context, and making final decisions before distribution.
